\ static "playfield" module example

module [forest]

\ there is no external/changeable map data in this example.
\ this IS the playfield.

\ data: tells the "visual list editor" what data is stored and where 
\ this list is (what file, what lines)
\ %playfieldobj is a descriptor that is either defined in this file, 
\ or is an imported "universal static entity" descriptor.  (doesn't matter.)

playfieldobj: tree1   <sprid> , x1 , y1 , x2 , y2 , 
playfieldobj: tree2   <sprid> , x1 , y1 , x2 , y2 , 

%playfieldobj data: forest.list   \ creates an wide %array called forest.list
    0 , 0 , tree1 ,   \ tree1 and tree2 are just strategies with no state
    0 , 0 , tree2 , 
    0 , 0 , tree1 , 
    0 , 0 , tree1 , 
    0 , 0 , tree2 , 
data;

: ~forest 
    [: a!> @a+ @a+ at @a+ draw ;] forest.list each ;

\ there is only one forest playfield, but we still need an object
\ that can plug into the system.
\ perhaps %system in turn derives from %actor, or the other way around
c: %forest  %system w h ;

%forest :: entity-count ( - n )
    forest.list #items ;

%forest :: entity-box ( n - x1. y1. x2. y2. )
    forest.list el@ a!> @a+ >p @a+ >p @a+ dims ;

%forest :: entity-solid? ( n - flag )
    drop true ;

\ all %forest needs is to render.  
%forest :: render
    ~forest ;

%forest manager: forest  \ this functions as an entry point.  forest gets stored in a static property of %forest
                        \ not sure if we could just use OBJECT or if %FOREST needs to have a stored "entry point"
    320. 240. w 2!      \ just a single screen
manager;

\ client-game.vfx:

import forest      \ our playfield
import zelda-like  \ top-down npc's with psuedo-3d physics

\ zelda-like npc's have a "z" property so they can jump/fall and cast a convincing shadow on the ground
\ but the forest doesn't have a concept of that, just a bunch of boxes, at the bases of the trees

zelda-like forest connect  \ CONNECT mutually adds the systems to each other's lists of cohorts

\ i suppose there are cases where one-directional registering would be needed
forest zelda-like register \ zelda-like knows about forest, forest does not know about zelda-like

: main
    \ just singleton systems so far
    just
    forest load  \ adds to the list of active %system's and starts it up
    zelda-like load
;

\ you do not have to LOAD systems to use them.
\ maybe you just want the visuals

: my-renderer
    show> ... forest render[&animate?] ... ;



\ zelda-like.vfx:

%zelda-like :: start
    physics>  
        \ query registered system's entities and send collision events back
        [:
            \ move and slide npcs ...
            [:
                {: sys :}
                sys entity-count for
                    my-lyr i sys entity-mask and if
                        i sys entity-box hit-me? if  me npc>id i sys entity-hit  then  
                        i sys entity-box push-me-out-of
                    then
                loop
            ;] each-cohort  \ only loaded-and-active systems that are registered with this system
        ;] each-active
;


